title: JNI version seems too high for Android
body:
**Describe the bug**

@Craigacp Thanks for your great work on Java API!

When compiling Java API for Android (with some necessary modifications), the compilation fails because `JNI_VERSION_1_8` [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/java/src/main/native/OrtJniUtil.c#L13) doesn't exist in `jni.h` of Android NDK. The highest jni version Android NDK has is `JNI_VERSION_1_6`.

Could the jni version be downgraded to 1.6 safely? Thanks! @Craigacp 

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Android
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): latest Android NDK

title: User/sheilk/winml adapter c api
body:
Description
1. Make the winml adapter api a c-abi that uses/enhances the onnxruntime c-abi.
2. Extend OrtTypeInfo to create Map and Sequence Info objects in the adapter.
3. Create the DML provider with the dml provider factory in the adapter, rather than on our own.
4. Move WinRT completely out of the adapter.
5. Isolate all onnx/ort calls into the ort static library that lives in the winml dll.
6. Make Map and Sequence do the minimum number of copies while still using the c-abi. This involves implementing the map and sequence types on the c-abi instead of the cxx apis.
7. Make the winml adapter dependent on the ort_api version.
8. Dont use globals to access the winml adapter, as we may want to create multiple engines concurrently with different ort versions in the future.
9. Use the c-abi directly, to prevent adding another projection layer between winml and ort.
10. Isolate all dml api calls in the ort lib, so that DML is just an implementation detail of the onnxruntime engine implementation, and not a detail of the winrt projection. WinML is now only aware of dx devices and d3d11/12 resources.

title: Fix exception handling in InferenceSession::Run
body:
**Description**: 
InferenceSession::Run needs to call OnRunEnd for any EP that OnRunStart was called for so they can cleanup. Currently it only calls OnRunEnd if the Status is OK. Due to this, if graph execution failed the CUDA EP will throw during shutdown as the per-thread information has not been cleaned up prior to the CUDA library shutting down.

Also update onnxruntime_perf_test to catch the exception from the call to Run and return a Status. Otherwise it exits with an 'unknown exception' error.

**Motivation and Context**
Whilst the exception from graph execution is gracefully returned as a Status, the issue with OnRunEnd not being called leads to an unhandled exception during shutdown.

**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
The onnxruntime shared library is linked without `-z noexecstack` flag, so the stack is executable as a result. This triggers security warnings specifically when using the Java API, as the JVM's loader emits a warning (but does not outright prevent the loading of the library). Here is an example of what type of warning the JVM makes https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2215#issuecomment-546967004
My environment creates an identical warning.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
https://wiki.ubuntu.com/SecurityTeam/Roadmap/ExecutableStacks seems to discuss marking inline assembly manually. Once again, I do not know the implications or best practices for this, so I think this issue is a good place to discuss possible solutions.

title: Optimize BatchNormalization to NCHWc Conv
body:
**Description**: Update the NCHWc transformer to convert BatchNormalization ops to NCHWc convolutions when the input tensor is already in NCHWc.

**Motivation and Context**
CNNs such as resnet50v2 and densenets have architectures where the blocks are arranged as BatchNormalization+Relu+Conv. The NCHWc transformer didn't have support for the leading BatchNormalization node, so the graph would be run with extra reorder ops that hurt performance. 

This change teaches the optimizer to rewrite the BatchNormalization as a depthwise 1x1 convolution when the input tensor is already in NCHWc format. I did it this way to avoid adding another com.microsoft.nchwc op that does the plain scale/bias. A little more performance could be squeezed out by special casing this path inside MLAS. Doing it this way also allowed the existing NchwcConv+Relu fusion to automatically work.

The model zoo version of resnet50v2 goes from 29->21ms on one system with 126->75 nodes.

title: Upgrade gtest to the latest version
body:
**Description**: 

Upgrade gtest to the latest version. However, because the newer version hit a bug in gcc, even though the bug is already fixed in the latest gcc version but we're using gcc 4.8.x and we can't change that,  so we have to do a compromise,  change our code a little bit to make it work.

Background:
<hr/>
From: Tiago 

Hi Changming, I'm looking at the Linux pipeline build failure with latest googletest. It's hitting this GCC bug: https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=51213 in this template: https://github.com/google/googletest/compare/9bda90b7e5e08c4c37a832d0cea218aed6af6470...703bd9caab50b139428cea1aaff9974ebee5742e#diff-92131a3467c5f3247170faff2fa23c25L886-R898 .
 
Basically, they use a template overload with SFINAE to detect whether an object is iterable:
```c++
template <class C,
          class Iterator = decltype(::std::declval<const C&>().begin()),
          class = decltype(::std::declval<const C&>().end()),
          class = decltype(++::std::declval<Iterator&>()),
          class = decltype(*::std::declval<Iterator>()),
          class = typename C::const_iterator>
IsContainer IsContainerTest(int /* dummy */) { 
```
The bug is that decltype(::std::declval<const C&>().begin()) makes GCC throw an invalid access instead of picking the next template overload if the class has begin(), but from a private inheritance (so if the member exists but is not accessible, GCC fails with "error: A is not an accessible base of B" instead of trying the next template overload). This was a bug in GCC.
<hr/>


**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
WinML would like to update the googletest submodule. They want some newer features (namely GTEST_SKIP to skip tests programmatically and be able to skip entire fixtures easily) and would need to update the submodule version.

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
